<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="fun2-reading" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>FUN-2 Reading</title>
    <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Things you should understand and know:
        <ul>
            <li>Lines in three-dimensional space</li>
            <li>Distance in three-dimensions</li>
            <li>Planes in three-dimensions</li>
            <li>The main features of ellipsoids, paraboloids, and hyperboloids</li>
            <li>The traces of quadric surfaces and how to form a surface from them</li>
            <li>The cylindrical coordinate system and how to locate points</li>
            <li>The spherical coordinate system and how to locate points</li>
        </ul></p>
        <p>Things you should be able to do:
        <ul>
            <li>Write the equation of a line in vector, parametric, and symmetric form</li>
            <li>Find the distance between a point to a line</li>
            <li>Write the equation of a plane in vector and scalar forms</li>
            <li>Find the distance between a point and a plane</li>
            <li>find the angle between two planes</li>
            <li>Identify and sketch cylinders</li>
            <li>Identify and sketch ellipsoids, paraboloids, and hyperboloids</li>
            <li>Find the equations of traces</li>
            <li>Use traces to sketch a quadric surface</li>
            <li>Convert between rectangular, cylindrical, and spherical coordinates</li>
        </ul></p>
      </li>
      <li><p>You will be assessed on the following criteria:
        <ul>
          <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
              that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
          <li><p>Equations of Lines and Planes: Write and interpret the equations 
            of lines and planes in various forms (vector, parametric, symmetric, scalar).</p></li>
          <li><p>Calculating Distances and Angles: Calculate distances between points, 
            lines, and planes, as well as angles between vectors and planes.</p></li>
          <li><p>Quadric Surfaces: Finding traces in two dimensions and sketching quadric surfaces in 
            three dimensions.  Identifying the surface type from its equation.</p></li>
          <li><p>Change of Coordinates: Convert between different coordinate systems (polar, cylindrical, 
            spherical) and understand the relationship between them.</p></li>
        </ul></p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>
        <p>All of the readings for this course come from the OpenStax Calculus 
            Volume 3 textbook, which is available for free online at 
            <url href="https://openstax.org/details/books/calculus-volume-3">
                https://openstax.org/details/books/calculus-volume-3</url>. You 
                can read the textbook online or download a PDF version. 
                The textbook is also available in print from various retailers 
                if you prefer a physical copy.</p>
        <p>For this lesson, you should read sections <url href="https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-3/pages/2-5-equations-of-lines-and-planes-in-space">
            2.5 Equations of Lines and Planes in Space</url>, <url href="https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-3/pages/2-6-quadric-surfaces">2.6 Quadric Surfaces</url>, and
            <url href="https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-3/pages/2-7-cylindrical-and-spherical-coordinates">2.7 Cylindrical and Spherical Coordinates</url>.. You should read through the sections carefully, 
            making sure to understand the definitions, examples, and key ideas. 
            You should also work through the exercises at the end of each section 
            to test your understanding and practice applying the concepts. Some of the 
            exercises at the end of the section are assigned in the WP assignments.</p>      
</worksheet>
